AWS EC2 Linux Setup (Clean Table Format)
Install Required Packages
Step	Command
Switch to root	sudo su
Install net-tools	yum install net-tools
Install ntpstat	yum install ntpstat
Install wget	yum install wget
Set Hostname
Step	Command
Set hostname	hostnamectl set-hostname <COMPONENT_NAME>
Create Splunk User and Directory
Step	Command
Create user	useradd splunk
Create group	groupadd splunk
Create directory	mkdir /opt/splunk
Set ownership	chown -R splunk:splunk /opt/splunk
Disable Transparent Huge Pages (THP)
Navigation & Setup
Step	Command
Go to directory	cd /etc/init.d/
Create script	vi disable_thp
Script Content
File	Content
disable_thp	bash<br>#!/bin/bash<br>### BEGIN INIT INFO<br># Provides: disable-thp<br># Required-Start: $local_fs<br># Default-Start: 2 3 4 5<br>### END INIT INFO<br><br>case $1 in<br>start)<br> if test -f /sys/kernel/mm/transparent_hugepage/enabled; then<br> thp_path=/sys/kernel/mm/transparent_hugepage<br> elif test -f /sys/kernel/mm/redhat_transparent_hugepage/enabled; then<br> thp_path=/sys/kernel/mm/redhat_transparent_hugepage<br> else<br> return 0<br> fi<br><br> echo 'never' > ${thp_path}/enabled<br> echo 'never' > ${thp_path}/defrag<br><br> if [[ $(cat ${thp_path}/khugepaged/defrag) =~ ^[0-1]+$ ]]; then<br> echo 0 > ${thp_path}/khugepaged/defrag<br> else<br> echo 'no' > ${thp_path}/khugepaged/defrag<br> fi<br> ;;<br>esac
Permissions & Startup
Step	Command
Verify file	cat disable_thp
Add permission	chmod 755 disable_thp
Add to startup	chkconfig --add disable_thp
Increase ulimit
Edit Config
Step	Command
Open file	vi /etc/security/limits.conf
Add Values
Setting	Value
soft nofile	64000
hard nofile	unlimited
soft nproc	16000
hard nproc	unlimited
soft data	8000000
hard data	unlimited
soft fsize	unlimited
hard fsize	unlimited
Apply Changes
Step	Command
Save file	:wq!
Reboot	reboot
Verify	ulimit -a splunk
Alternate verify	cat /etc/security/limits.conf
Verify THP is Disabled
Step	Command
Check enabled	cat /sys/kernel/mm/transparent_hugepage/enabled
Check defrag	cat /sys/kernel/mm/transparent_hugepage/defrag
Expected output	never
Enable Splunk Bootstart
Step	Command
Switch user	sudo su
Enable bootstart	/opt/splunk/bin/splunk enable boot-start -user splunk
Honest Notes (Don’t Ignore)
Issue	Reality
OS compatibility	Works for RHEL/CentOS, not Kali/Ubuntu directly
chkconfig	Legacy (use systemctl in modern systems)
THP method	Outdated approach
Production use	Needs tuning
